Hello [~accountid:5d427f60e4777b0db2f0e1c5] ,

Would you have the Button wpa_supplicant  log ?

You can retrieve it in the full journalctl log and filter on wpa_supplicant in the following way (or just grep on “wpa_supplicant”):

{noformat} journalctl -u wpa_supplicant@wlan0{noformat}

Please, could you also make sure the logLevel is set to “osa_logging_debug“

You can set it directly on the board via

{noformat}g5configcli -s application.logLevel -t string -v osa_logging_debug{noformat}

Or via the button-control-cli command

{noformat}PS D:\Barco\Tools\ButtonControlCLI\01.16.00.1.16.0-0001_win> ./button-control-cli -L -l 1024 -1 0x0600 -2 0x01b5 -3 0xFF00 -4 0x02 --caCrt .\test_fruitesse_new\ClickShare_Root_CA.cert --clientCrt .\test_fruitesse_new\cert.pem --clientKey .\test_fruitesse_new\privkey.pem --setLogLevel osa_logging_debug{noformat}

Digging more in details about the issue.

The SSID is skipped during scanning by wpa_supplicant due to the following check (wpa_supplicant/event.c):

{noformat}	if (wpas_get_ssid_pmf(wpa_s, ssid) == MGMT_FRAME_PROTECTION_REQUIRED &&
	    (!(ssid->key_mgmt & WPA_KEY_MGMT_OWE) || ssid->owe_only)) {
		if (debug_print)
			wpa_dbg(wpa_s, MSG_DEBUG,
				"   skip - MFP Required but network not MFP Capable");
		return 0;
	}{noformat}

→ OWE = “Opportunistic Wireless Encryption”

OWE:

“Opportunistic Wireless Encryption (OWE) is a Wi-Fi security mechanism standardized under IEEE 802.11 and certified by the Wi-Fi Alliance as part of WPA3.
It provides encryption for open Wi-Fi networks without requiring user authentication, enhancing security for public or guest networks.
OWE Transition Mode enables backward compatibility, allowing OWE-capable and legacy devices to coexist on the same network.“ ([https://openwrt.org/docs/guide-user/network/wifi/owe_encryption|https://openwrt.org/docs/guide-user/network/wifi/owe_encryption|smart-link] )
